## Reactor Backpressure: Controlling Demand in WebFlux

### What's happening
Reactive Streams backpressure works via `request(n)` — the subscriber signals how many items it can consume. Kafka source emits faster than the DB subscriber requests. When the internal buffer overflows, Reactor throws `OverflowException`.

### The broken pipeline
```java
// Dangerous: no backpressure control
kafkaReceiver.receive()  // emits 10k/s
    .flatMap(record -> dbRepository.save(record.value()))  // handles 1k/s
    .subscribe();
// flatMap defaults to concurrency=256 and unbounded inner subscriptions
```

### Fix 1: Bound flatMap concurrency
```java
kafkaReceiver.receive()
    .flatMap(
        record -> dbRepository.save(record.value()),
        8,     // max concurrent DB writes
        32     // prefetch per inner publisher
    )
    .doOnNext(result -> log.debug("Saved: {}", result.getId()))
    .subscribe();
```
With 8 concurrent writes at 125ms each = ~1,000 writes/second, matching DB capacity.

### Fix 2: Bounded buffer with drop strategy
```java
kafkaReceiver.receive()
    .onBackpressureBuffer(
        5_000,                         // buffer capacity
        dropped -> {
            droppedCounter.increment();
            log.warn("Dropped record: {}", dropped.value().getId());
        },
        BufferOverflowStrategy.DROP_OLDEST
    )
    .flatMap(record -> dbRepository.save(record.value()), 8, 32)
    .subscribe();
```

### Fix 3: Windowed batching for higher throughput
```java
kafkaReceiver.receive()
    .window(Duration.ofMillis(100))   // 100ms windows
    .flatMap(window -> window
        .collectList()
        .flatMap(batch -> dbRepository.saveAll(batch))  // batch insert
    , 4)  // 4 concurrent windows
    .subscribe();
```
Batch inserts amortize DB overhead — 500 records in one INSERT vs 500 individual writes.

### Fix 4: Explicit request(n) with BaseSubscriber
```java
kafkaReceiver.receive().subscribe(new BaseSubscriber<ReceiverRecord<?, ?>>() {
    @Override
    protected void hookOnSubscribe(Subscription s) {
        request(100); // initially request 100
    }

    @Override
    protected void hookOnNext(ReceiverRecord<?, ?> record) {
        processAndSave(record).subscribe(done -> request(1)); // request 1 more after each
    }
});
```
Full manual control — processes one item at a time, requests next only when done.

