## Event-Driven Cache Invalidation

### Problem with TTL-only invalidation
TTL is appropriate for data with predictable staleness. Price changes are event-driven: the moment a price changes, all cached copies are stale. 5-minute TTL means up to 5-minute exposure to wrong prices.

### Solution: Event-driven invalidation pipeline

#### Step 1: Publish price-changed events
```java
@Service
@Transactional
public class PricingService {
    public void updatePrice(String productId, BigDecimal newPrice) {
        pricingRepository.updatePrice(productId, newPrice);
        // Publish after DB commit via Outbox or direct event
        eventPublisher.publishEvent(new PriceChangedEvent(productId, newPrice));
    }
}
```

#### Step 2: Cache invalidation consumer
```java
@Component
public class PriceCacheInvalidator {
    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    private final MeterRegistry metrics;

    @KafkaListener(topics = "price-changes", concurrency = "4")
    public void onPriceChanged(PriceChangedEvent event) {
        String key = "price:" + event.getProductId();
        redis.delete(key);
        metrics.counter("cache.invalidations",
            "reason", "price-change").increment();
        log.info("Invalidated cache for product {}", event.getProductId());
    }
}
```

#### Step 3: Handle flash sale bulk invalidation safely
```java
@KafkaListener(topics = "flash-sale-started")
public void onFlashSaleStarted(FlashSaleEvent event) {
    // Stagger invalidations to prevent thundering herd
    List<String> productIds = event.getProductIds();
    int batchSize = 50;
    for (int i = 0; i < productIds.size(); i += batchSize) {
        List<String> batch = productIds.subList(i, Math.min(i + batchSize, productIds.size()));
        List<String> keys = batch.stream()
            .map(id -> "price:" + id)
            .collect(Collectors.toList());
        redis.delete(keys);
        // Small delay between batches to stagger DB reads
        try { Thread.sleep(50); } catch (InterruptedException e) { Thread.currentThread().interrupt(); }
    }
}
```

#### Step 4: Cache-aside with short TTL as safety net
```java
public BigDecimal getPrice(String productId) {
    String key = "price:" + productId;
    String cached = redis.opsForValue().get(key);
    if (cached != null) return new BigDecimal(cached);

    BigDecimal price = pricingRepository.findPrice(productId);
    redis.opsForValue().set(key, price.toString(),
        Duration.ofMinutes(10)); // safety-net TTL
    return price;
}
```
The event invalidates immediately; TTL is a fallback for missed events.

