## Backend for Frontend (BFF): 7 Calls → 1

### Why 7 calls is a mobile problem
- Mobile networks: 50-100ms per round trip
- 7 sequential calls = 350-700ms just in latency
- 7 parallel calls still means 7 × connection overhead, battery drain, complexity
- Mobile app must handle 7 partial failure modes

### BFF Architecture
```
Mobile App
    ↓ 1 call: GET /bff/product/{id}/detail
BFF Service (mobile-bff)
    ↓ 7 parallel calls (internal network, ~1ms each)
    ├── product-service
    ├── pricing-service
    ├── inventory-service
    ├── reviews-service
    ├── recommendations-service
    ├── seller-service
    └── shipping-service
```

### BFF implementation with CompletableFuture fan-out
```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/bff")
public class ProductDetailBff {
    // Each client has its own RestTemplate/WebClient

    @GetMapping("/product/{id}/detail")
    public ProductDetailResponse getProductDetail(
            @PathVariable String id,
            @RequestHeader("X-Device-Type") String deviceType) {

        // Fan out to all 7 services in parallel
        CompletableFuture<ProductInfo>       productFuture     = productClient.getAsync(id);
        CompletableFuture<PricingInfo>       pricingFuture     = pricingClient.getAsync(id);
        CompletableFuture<InventoryStatus>   inventoryFuture   = inventoryClient.getAsync(id);
        CompletableFuture<List<Review>>      reviewsFuture     = reviewsClient.getTopAsync(id, 5);
        CompletableFuture<List<Product>>     recsFuture        = recsClient.getAsync(id);
        CompletableFuture<SellerInfo>        sellerFuture      = sellerClient.getAsync(id);
        CompletableFuture<List<ShipOption>>  shippingFuture    = shippingClient.getAsync(id);

        // Wait for critical path; allow non-critical to degrade
        ProductInfo product = productFuture.join();         // critical: fail if missing
        PricingInfo pricing = pricingFuture.join();         // critical: fail if missing
        InventoryStatus inv = inventoryFuture.join();       // critical

        List<Review> reviews = getOrDefault(reviewsFuture,     Collections.emptyList());
        List<Product> recs   = getOrDefault(recsFuture,        Collections.emptyList());
        SellerInfo seller    = getOrDefault(sellerFuture,       SellerInfo.unknown());
        List<ShipOption> ship = getOrDefault(shippingFuture,   Collections.emptyList());

        return ProductDetailResponse.builder()
            .product(product)
            .pricing(pricing)
            .inventory(inv)
            .reviews(reviews)
            .recommendations(recs)
            .seller(seller)
            .shippingOptions(ship)
            .build();
    }

    private <T> T getOrDefault(CompletableFuture<T> future, T fallback) {
        try {
            return future.get(800, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.warn("Non-critical service timed out: {}", e.getMessage());
            return fallback;
        }
    }
}
```

### Mobile-specific response shaping
```java
// BFF shapes response for mobile screen size
// Desktop BFF would return full data
public ProductDetailResponse shapeForMobile(ProductDetailResponse full) {
    return full.toBuilder()
        .reviews(full.getReviews().subList(0, 3))     // top 3 only
        .recommendations(full.getRecommendations().subList(0, 4))  // 4 items
        .description(truncate(full.getProduct().getDescription(), 500))  // shorter
        .build();
}
```

### Result
- 7 external calls → 1 (mobile perspective)
- Latency: dominated by slowest critical service, typically 200-400ms on internal network
- Partial degradation: page loads even if recommendations/reviews timeout

