## Silent Scheduled Job Failure: Root Cause and Prevention

### Root cause: exception killed the scheduler thread
Spring's default `@Scheduled` uses a single-threaded `ThreadPoolTaskScheduler`. If one execution throws an uncaught `RuntimeException`, the thread terminates. Subsequent executions never start — no log, no alert, just silence.

```java
// The bug: uncaught exception kills the thread
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 3_600_000)
public void processPayouts() {
    List<Payout> pending = payoutRepository.findPending();
    for (Payout p : pending) {
        processOne(p); // throws NullPointerException on malformed data — thread dies here
    }
}
```

### Fix 1: Catch all exceptions in scheduled methods
```java
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 3_600_000)
public void processPayouts() {
    try {
        doProcessPayouts();
        lastSuccessfulRun = Instant.now();
        jobSuccessCounter.increment();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        log.error("Payout job failed — will retry next interval", e);
        jobFailureCounter.increment();
        alertingService.fire("PayoutJobFailed", e.getMessage());
        // DO NOT rethrow — scheduler thread must survive
    }
}
```

### Fix 2: Dead-man's switch alert (most important)
```java
@Component
public class PayoutJobHealthMonitor {
    private volatile Instant lastSuccessfulRun = Instant.now();

    @Scheduled(fixedDelay = 300_000) // check every 5 minutes
    public void checkJobHealth() {
        Duration gap = Duration.between(lastSuccessfulRun, Instant.now());
        if (gap.toHours() > 2) { // expected: runs every hour
            alertingService.fire("PayoutJobSilent",
                "No successful payout run in " + gap.toMinutes() + " minutes");
        }
    }

    // Expose via Actuator health check
    @Bean
    public HealthIndicator payoutJobHealth() {
        return () -> {
            Duration gap = Duration.between(lastSuccessfulRun, Instant.now());
            if (gap.toHours() <= 2) return Health.up()
                .withDetail("lastRun", lastSuccessfulRun).build();
            return Health.down()
                .withDetail("lastRun", lastSuccessfulRun)
                .withDetail("gapMinutes", gap.toMinutes()).build();
        };
    }
}
```

### Fix 3: ShedLock for multi-instance safety + persistence
```java
@Scheduled(fixedDelay = 3_600_000)
@SchedulerLock(name = "processPayouts",
    lockAtLeastFor = "PT50M",  // hold lock 50 min min
    lockAtMostFor  = "PT60M"   // release lock if job hangs > 60 min
)
public void processPayouts() { ... }

// ShedLock stores last execution in DB — you can query it
// SELECT name, lock_until, locked_at FROM shedlock WHERE name = 'processPayouts';
```

### Fix 4: Dedicated thread pool for scheduled jobs
```java
@Configuration
public class SchedulerConfig {
    @Bean
    public TaskScheduler taskScheduler() {
        ThreadPoolTaskScheduler scheduler = new ThreadPoolTaskScheduler();
        scheduler.setPoolSize(4);  // separate thread per job category
        scheduler.setThreadNamePrefix("sched-");
        // Critical: error handler prevents one job's failure from killing pool
        scheduler.setErrorHandler(t ->
            log.error("Unhandled scheduler error", t));
        return scheduler;
    }
}
```

message-queue-vs-event-stream.answer:
## Decoupling Email via Message Queue

### Before: synchronous coupling
```
Checkout ──────────────────────────────── Email Provider
         → HTTP call (2-3s, can timeout)
         ← response (or timeout exception)
```

### After: asynchronous queue
```
Checkout → publish message (1ms) → Queue → Email Worker → Email Provider
         ← return immediately
```

### Implementation with Spring + RabbitMQ

#### Publisher (checkout service)
```java
@Service
public class CheckoutService {
    private final RabbitTemplate rabbitTemplate;

    @Transactional
    public CheckoutResult checkout(CheckoutRequest req) {
        Order order = processOrder(req); // inventory + payment

        // Publish email request — fire and forget
        // Note: for guaranteed delivery, use Outbox pattern instead
        rabbitTemplate.convertAndSend(
            "notifications.exchange",
            "order.confirmation",
            new OrderConfirmationMessage(order.getId(), req.getEmail())
        );

        return CheckoutResult.success(order.getId());
        // Returns in ~400ms — email publishing adds ~1ms
    }
}
```

#### Consumer (email worker service)
```java
@Component
public class OrderConfirmationConsumer {

    @RabbitListener(queues = "order-confirmation-queue")
    public void handleOrderConfirmation(OrderConfirmationMessage msg) {
        // Idempotency check: have we sent this email already?
        if (emailAuditLog.alreadySent(msg.getOrderId())) {
            log.info("Skipping duplicate email for order {}", msg.getOrderId());
            return;
        }

        try {
            emailService.sendOrderConfirmation(msg.getEmail(), msg.getOrderId());
            emailAuditLog.markSent(msg.getOrderId()); // record success
        } catch (EmailException e) {
            // Message returns to queue (NACK) — RabbitMQ will redeliver
            throw new AmqpRejectAndDontRequeueException("Permanent failure", e);
            // OR: just throw e to trigger requeue
        }
    }
}
```

#### Queue configuration with dead-letter
```java
@Configuration
public class RabbitConfig {
    @Bean
    public Queue orderConfirmationQueue() {
        return QueueBuilder.durable("order-confirmation-queue")
            .withArgument("x-dead-letter-exchange", "order-confirmation.dlx")
            .withArgument("x-message-ttl", 86_400_000) // 24h max age
            .withArgument("x-max-length", 100_000)     // max 100k messages
            .build();
    }

    @Bean
    public Queue orderConfirmationDlq() {
        return QueueBuilder.durable("order-confirmation-dlq").build();
    }
}
```

### Guarantees this design provides
- **Checkout availability**: email provider outage has zero impact
- **At-least-once delivery**: RabbitMQ persists messages, redeliver if consumer crashes
- **Retry with backoff**: consumer failure requeues message
- **Overflow protection**: max-length prevents unbounded memory growth

db-connection-pool-exhaustion.answer:
## Diagnosing and Fixing a HikariCP Connection Leak

### Step 1: Enable leak detection
```yaml
spring:
  datasource:
    hikari:
      leak-detection-threshold: 10000  # ms — log stack trace if connection held > 10s
      connection-timeout: 30000
      maximum-pool-size: 20
      minimum-idle: 5
```
This logs a stack trace showing WHERE the connection was acquired — the leak source.

### Step 2: Check DB for long-held connections
```sql
-- PostgreSQL: see all connections and their state
SELECT pid, usename, application_name, state, query_start,
       now() - query_start AS duration, query
FROM pg_stat_activity
WHERE datname = 'mydb'
ORDER BY duration DESC NULLS LAST;

-- Find idle connections held by the app (leaked)
SELECT pid, state, now() - state_change AS idle_duration
FROM pg_stat_activity
WHERE state = 'idle' AND application_name = 'myapp'
ORDER BY idle_duration DESC;
```

### Common leak pattern: ResultSet not closed
```java
// Leaked: connection not returned if exception occurs mid-read
public List<Order> findOrders(long customerId) throws SQLException {
    Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection();  // acquired
    Statement stmt = conn.createStatement();
    ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery("SELECT * FROM orders WHERE ...");
    List<Order> result = new ArrayList<>();
    while (rs.next()) {
        result.add(mapRow(rs)); // throws RuntimeException on malformed data
    }
    conn.close(); // NEVER REACHED if mapRow threw
    return result;
}
```

### Fix: try-with-resources
```java
public List<Order> findOrders(long customerId) throws SQLException {
    try (Connection conn = dataSource.getConnection();
         PreparedStatement stmt = conn.prepareStatement(
             "SELECT id, status, total FROM orders WHERE customer_id = ?");
    ) {
        stmt.setLong(1, customerId);
        try (ResultSet rs = stmt.executeQuery()) {
            List<Order> result = new ArrayList<>();
            while (rs.next()) {
                result.add(mapRow(rs));
            }
            return result;
        }
    }
    // Connection, Statement, ResultSet auto-closed even on exception
}
```

### Spring JDBC / JPA: almost impossible to leak
```java
// JdbcTemplate manages connections internally
@Repository
public class OrderRepository {
    private final JdbcTemplate jdbc;

    public List<Order> findByCustomer(long customerId) {
        return jdbc.query(
            "SELECT id, status, total FROM orders WHERE customer_id = ?",
            (rs, row) -> mapRow(rs),
            customerId
        );
        // Connection automatically returned to pool after query
    }
}
```

### Monitor for trend before next exhaustion
```java
// Expose HikariCP metrics via Micrometer
@Bean
public MeterRegistryCustomizer<MeterRegistry> hikariMetrics(DataSource ds) {
    return registry -> {
        if (ds instanceof HikariDataSource hds) {
            new HikariCPMetrics(hds).bindTo(registry);
        }
    };
}
// Alert on: hikaricp_connections_active > 18 (90% of pool) for > 5 minutes
```

api-rate-limiting-design.answer:
## Distributed Rate Limiting with Redis

### Why in-memory fails at scale
6 instances × 100 req/min limit = 600 req/min effective limit. The counter must be global, not per-instance.

### Solution 1: Redis fixed window (simple)
```java
@Component
public class RedisRateLimiter {
    private final RedisTemplate<String, String> redis;
    private static final int LIMIT = 100;
    private static final int WINDOW_SECONDS = 60;

    public boolean isAllowed(String userId) {
        String key = "rate:" + userId + ":" + currentWindowKey();

        Long count = redis.opsForValue().increment(key);
        if (count == 1) {
            // First request in window — set expiry
            redis.expire(key, Duration.ofSeconds(WINDOW_SECONDS));
        }
        return count <= LIMIT;
    }

    private String currentWindowKey() {
        // Bucket by minute: "2024-01-15T10:23"
        return Instant.now().truncatedTo(ChronoUnit.MINUTES).toString();
    }
}
```
**Problem**: burst at window boundary — 100 at end of minute + 100 at start of next = 200 in 2 seconds.

### Solution 2: Sliding window with Redis sorted set
```java
public boolean isAllowed(String userId) {
    String key = "ratelimit:sliding:" + userId;
    long now = System.currentTimeMillis();
    long windowStart = now - 60_000; // 60 seconds ago

    // Atomic Lua script: remove old entries + count + conditionally add
    String luaScript = """
        local key = KEYS[1]
        local now = tonumber(ARGV[1])
        local window_start = tonumber(ARGV[2])
        local limit = tonumber(ARGV[3])
        local member = ARGV[4]

        -- Remove entries outside the window
        redis.call('ZREMRANGEBYSCORE', key, 0, window_start)

        -- Count remaining
        local count = redis.call('ZCARD', key)

        if count < limit then
            redis.call('ZADD', key, now, member)
            redis.call('EXPIRE', key, 70)  -- slightly longer than window
            return 1  -- allowed
        end
        return 0  -- denied
        """;

    Long result = redis.execute(
        RedisScript.of(luaScript, Long.class),
        List.of(key),
        String.valueOf(now),
        String.valueOf(windowStart),
        String.valueOf(LIMIT),
        now + "-" + UUID.randomUUID() // unique member
    );
    return result != null && result == 1L;
}
```

### Solution 3: Redis token bucket (Bucket4j + Redis)
```java
// Bucket4j with Redis backend — production-grade
@Bean
public ProxyManager<String> redisProxyManager(RedissonClient redisson) {
    return Bucket4jRedisson.builderFor(redisson)
        .build();
}

public boolean isAllowed(String userId) {
    BucketConfiguration config = BucketConfiguration.builder()
        .addLimit(Bandwidth.classic(100, Refill.greedy(100, Duration.ofMinutes(1))))
        .build();

    Bucket bucket = proxyManager.builder()
        .build(userId, () -> config);

    return bucket.tryConsume(1);
}
```

### Handling Redis unavailability
```java
public boolean isAllowed(String userId) {
    try {
        return redisRateLimit(userId);
    } catch (RedisConnectionFailureException e) {
        log.warn("Redis unavailable for rate limiting — applying local limit", e);
        // Fail-open: use local in-memory counter as degraded fallback
        return localFallbackLimiter.isAllowed(userId);
        // Fail-closed: return false (safer, but affects all users)
    }
}
```

distributed-file-storage-s3.answer:
## Large File Uploads: Multipart S3 Upload

### Why large uploads fail
Single-part uploads stream the entire file through your service → S3. With a 5GB file at 10 Mbps = 66 minutes. HTTP connection timeout (usually 30-120s for load balancers) kills it mid-transfer. Even without timeout, a single TCP hiccup restarts the entire upload.

### Solution 1: S3 Transfer Manager (managed multipart)
```java
@Service
public class VideoUploadService {
    private final S3TransferManager transferManager;

    public VideoUploadService(S3Client s3Client) {
        this.transferManager = S3TransferManager.builder()
            .s3Client(s3Client)
            .build();
        // TransferManager automatically uses multipart for files > 8MB
        // Default part size: 8MB, min concurrent parts: 1, max: 8
    }

    public String uploadVideo(String bucket, String key, Path filePath) {
        FileUpload upload = transferManager.uploadFile(req -> req
            .putObjectRequest(put -> put
                .bucket(bucket)
                .key(key)
                .contentType("video/mp4"))
            .source(filePath)
            .build()
        );

        CompletedFileUpload result = upload.completionFuture()
            .join(); // blocks until all parts uploaded + completed

        return result.response().eTag();
    }
}
```

### Solution 2: Direct browser upload with pre-signed URL (best for large files)
```java
// Backend: generate pre-signed URL — browser uploads directly to S3
@PostMapping("/upload/initiate")
public PresignedUploadResponse initiateUpload(
        @RequestBody UploadRequest req, Principal user) {

    String key = "videos/" + user.getName() + "/" + UUID.randomUUID() + ".mp4";

    // Option A: single pre-signed PUT (< 5GB)
    PutObjectPresignRequest presignReq = PutObjectPresignRequest.builder()
        .signatureDuration(Duration.ofHours(1))
        .putObjectRequest(put -> put.bucket(videoBucket).key(key)
            .contentType(req.getContentType()))
        .build();

    PresignedPutObjectRequest presigned = s3Presigner.presignPutObject(presignReq);

    // Option B: multipart with pre-signed part URLs (> 5GB or resumable)
    return PresignedUploadResponse.builder()
        .uploadUrl(presigned.url().toString())
        .objectKey(key)
        .build();
}

// After S3 confirms upload, browser notifies backend:
@PostMapping("/upload/confirm")
public void confirmUpload(@RequestBody UploadConfirmation confirmation) {
    // Verify ETag matches, mark video as ready, trigger processing
    videoRepository.markUploaded(confirmation.getObjectKey());
    eventPublisher.publish(new VideoUploadedEvent(confirmation.getObjectKey()));
}
```

### Cleanup incomplete multipart uploads (cost control)
```java
// S3 lifecycle rule to abort incomplete multipart uploads
// Add to bucket lifecycle configuration:
// AbortIncompleteMultipartUpload: DaysAfterInitiation: 1
// Also add programmatically:
@Scheduled(cron = "0 0 2 * * *") // nightly
public void cleanupIncompleteUploads() {
    ListMultipartUploadsResponse response = s3.listMultipartUploads(
        r -> r.bucket(videoBucket)
    );
    Instant cutoff = Instant.now().minus(Duration.ofHours(24));
    response.uploads().stream()
        .filter(u -> u.initiated().isBefore(cutoff))
        .forEach(u -> s3.abortMultipartUpload(
            r -> r.bucket(videoBucket).key(u.key()).uploadId(u.uploadId())
        ));
}
```

notification-system-design-java.answer:
## Idempotent Notification Processing

### Why duplicates happen with at-least-once delivery
Offset commit happens after processing. If pod restarts after sending email but before committing offset, Kafka redelivers the message. At-least-once = possibly more than once.

```
Consumer: process message → SEND EMAIL (success)
           pod restarts here
Consumer: offset NOT committed → Kafka redelivers → SEND EMAIL AGAIN
```

### Solution 1: DB idempotency log
```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "notification_log",
       uniqueConstraints = @UniqueConstraint(columnNames = {"notification_type", "message_id"}))
public class NotificationLog {
    @Id @GeneratedValue
    private Long id;
    private String notificationType;
    private String messageId;   // Kafka message key or business ID
    private String recipient;
    private Instant sentAt;
    private String status; // SENT, FAILED
}
```

```java
@KafkaListener(topics = "order-confirmations")
@Transactional
public void handleOrderConfirmation(
        OrderConfirmedEvent event,
        @Header(KafkaHeaders.RECEIVED_MESSAGE_KEY) String messageKey) {

    String dedupeKey = "ORDER_CONFIRMATION:" + messageKey;

    // Check and lock atomically — prevents race between concurrent consumers
    if (notificationLogRepo.existsByNotificationTypeAndMessageId(
            "ORDER_CONFIRMATION", messageKey)) {
        log.info("Skipping duplicate notification for message {}", messageKey);
        return;
    }

    try {
        emailService.sendOrderConfirmation(event);
        notificationLogRepo.save(new NotificationLog(
            "ORDER_CONFIRMATION", messageKey,
            event.getEmail(), Instant.now(), "SENT"
        ));
    } catch (EmailException e) {
        notificationLogRepo.save(new NotificationLog(
            "ORDER_CONFIRMATION", messageKey,
            event.getEmail(), Instant.now(), "FAILED"
        ));
        throw e; // trigger retry
    }
}
```

### Solution 2: Redis idempotency with TTL (faster, lower durability)
```java
public boolean markAndCheckSent(String messageId, String notificationType) {
    String key = "notif:sent:" + notificationType + ":" + messageId;
    // SETNX: set only if not exists — returns true if we were first
    Boolean isNew = redis.opsForValue().setIfAbsent(
        key, "sent", Duration.ofDays(7)
    );
    return Boolean.TRUE.equals(isNew); // true = process, false = duplicate
}

@KafkaListener(topics = "order-confirmations")
public void handleOrderConfirmation(OrderConfirmedEvent event, ...) {
    if (!idempotencyService.markAndCheckSent(messageKey, "ORDER_CONFIRMATION")) {
        log.info("Duplicate — skipping");
        return;
    }
    emailService.sendOrderConfirmation(event);
}
```

### Choose the right key for deduplication
```
Good keys:
  - Kafka message key (set by producer to orderId)
  - Business event ID: order.confirmed.{orderId}.{version}
  - Idempotency-Key from upstream API

Bad keys:
  - Kafka offset alone (partition-relative, changes after compaction)
  - Timestamp (collision-prone)
  - UUID generated at consumer time (different per delivery)
```

senior-production-incidents.answer:
## Silent Data Corruption: Investigation and Remediation

### Phase 1: Quantify the damage
```sql
-- Find accounts where stored balance doesn't match sum of transactions
SELECT
    a.id AS account_id,
    a.balance AS stored_balance,
    SUM(t.amount) AS computed_balance,
    a.balance - SUM(t.amount) AS discrepancy
FROM accounts a
JOIN transactions t ON t.account_id = a.id
GROUP BY a.id, a.balance
HAVING ABS(a.balance - SUM(t.amount)) > 0.01
ORDER BY ABS(a.balance - SUM(t.amount)) DESC;
```

### Phase 2: Find the root cause — lost update
```java
// BUG: read-modify-write without locking
public void debit(long accountId, BigDecimal amount) {
    Account account = accountRepository.findById(accountId).get(); // READ
    account.setBalance(account.getBalance().subtract(amount));     // MODIFY
    accountRepository.save(account);                               // WRITE
    // Two concurrent debits both read balance=100, both subtract 10,
    // both save 90 — one debit is lost
}
```

```java
// FIX A: Optimistic locking with @Version
@Entity
public class Account {
    @Id private Long id;
    private BigDecimal balance;
    @Version private Long version; // auto-incremented on each update
}
// Concurrent update throws OptimisticLockingFailureException — retry or fail fast

// FIX B: Pessimistic locking (SELECT FOR UPDATE)
@Repository
public interface AccountRepository extends JpaRepository<Account, Long> {
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("SELECT a FROM Account a WHERE a.id = :id")
    Optional<Account> findByIdForUpdate(@Param("id") Long id);
}

// FIX C: Atomic DB operation (no read-modify-write in app)
@Modifying
@Query("UPDATE Account a SET a.balance = a.balance - :amount WHERE a.id = :id AND a.balance >= :amount")
int debitAtomic(@Param("id") Long id, @Param("amount") BigDecimal amount);
// Returns 0 if balance insufficient — no negative balance possible
```

### Phase 3: Remediation without downtime
```java
@Service
public class BalanceReconciliationJob {

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public List<BalanceDiscrepancy> findDiscrepancies(int batchSize, long fromAccountId) {
        // Process in batches — don't load all 50M accounts at once
        return jdbcTemplate.query("""
            SELECT a.id, a.balance,
                   COALESCE(SUM(t.amount), 0) AS computed
            FROM accounts a
            LEFT JOIN transactions t ON t.account_id = a.id
            WHERE a.id > ?
            GROUP BY a.id, a.balance
            HAVING ABS(a.balance - COALESCE(SUM(t.amount), 0)) > 0.01
            ORDER BY a.id LIMIT ?
            """,
            (rs, row) -> new BalanceDiscrepancy(
                rs.getLong("id"),
                rs.getBigDecimal("balance"),
                rs.getBigDecimal("computed")
            ),
            fromAccountId, batchSize
        );
    }

    @Transactional
    public void correctBalance(BalanceDiscrepancy disc) {
        // Create correction transaction for audit trail
        Transaction correction = Transaction.builder()
            .accountId(disc.getAccountId())
            .amount(disc.getComputed().subtract(disc.getStored()))
            .type(TransactionType.BALANCE_CORRECTION)
            .reference("RECONCILIATION-" + Instant.now())
            .build();
        transactionRepository.save(correction);

        // Update balance atomically
        accountRepository.setBalance(disc.getAccountId(), disc.getComputed());
    }
}
```

### Phase 4: Prevention
- Nightly reconciliation job as ongoing monitoring
- Alert if discrepancy count > 0
- Add DB constraint: balance cannot go negative
- Mandatory code review for any balance mutation code

traffic-spike-scalability.answer:
## Handling 20x Traffic Spikes: Multi-Layer Strategy

### Why the crash happens
Tomcat default: 200 threads. At 10k RPS with 20ms average response time: 10000 × 0.020 = 200 threads needed steady-state. Any latency spike fills the thread pool. Connection queue overflows → `ConnectException` on clients. Service stops responding.

### Layer 1: Protect with rate limiting and circuit breakers at the edge
```yaml
# API Gateway / load balancer level
# Never let raw traffic reach all instances
nginx:
  limit_req_zone: $binary_remote_addr zone=checkout:10m rate=100r/s
  limit_req: zone=checkout burst=200 nodelay
```

### Layer 2: Virtual threads (Java 21) — massive concurrency cheaply
```yaml
# application.yml — Spring Boot 3.2+
spring:
  threads:
    virtual:
      enabled: true  # Tomcat uses virtual threads per request
```
With virtual threads, 10k concurrent requests use 10k virtual threads but only as many OS threads as CPU cores. Blocking I/O (DB, HTTP) parks the virtual thread without consuming an OS thread. This alone handles the thread exhaustion problem for I/O-bound workloads.

### Layer 3: WebFlux for fully non-blocking I/O
```java
@RestController
public class ProductController {
    private final WebClient inventoryClient;
    private final ReactiveRedisTemplate<String, String> redis;

    @GetMapping("/products/{id}")
    public Mono<ProductResponse> getProduct(@PathVariable String id) {
        return redis.opsForValue().get("product:" + id)  // non-blocking cache
            .map(json -> parseProduct(json))
            .switchIfEmpty(
                inventoryClient.get().uri("/inventory/" + id)
                    .retrieve()
                    .bodyToMono(InventoryInfo.class)
                    .flatMap(inv -> buildResponse(id, inv))
            );
        // Entire pipeline: 0 threads blocked waiting for I/O
        // Handles 10k req/s on 8 CPU cores
    }
}
```

### Layer 4: Cache aggressively for read-heavy flash sales
```java
// Cache product data — flash sale reads the same product pages repeatedly
@Cacheable(value = "products", key = "#id", unless = "#result == null")
public ProductResponse getProduct(String id) { ... }

// Pre-warm cache before flash sale
@EventListener(ApplicationReadyEvent.class)
public void prewarmCache() {
    if (flashSaleService.isFlashSaleImminent()) {
        flashSaleService.getUpcomingProductIds()
            .forEach(this::getProduct); // load into cache
    }
}
```

### Layer 5: Horizontal auto-scaling
```yaml
# Kubernetes HPA — scale out before the spike
apiVersion: autoscaling/v2
kind: HorizontalPodAutoscaler
spec:
  minReplicas: 3
  maxReplicas: 20
  metrics:
    - type: Resource
      resource:
        name: cpu
        target:
          type: Utilization
          averageUtilization: 60  # scale before saturation
  behavior:
    scaleUp:
      stabilizationWindowSeconds: 30
      policies:
        - type: Pods
          value: 4
          periodSeconds: 30  # add 4 pods every 30s
```

### Layer 6: Graceful degradation under extreme load
```java
// Serve stale cache for non-critical data rather than failing
@GetMapping("/recommendations")
public Flux<Product> getRecommendations(@RequestParam String userId) {
    return recommendationService.get(userId)
        .timeout(Duration.ofMillis(200))
        .onErrorReturn(TimeoutException.class, getCachedFallback(userId));
}
```
